<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-149-355 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 770 613</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  May 22 1991 n1681* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unisys plans to ship its 88000-based Unix systems in US, Europethis year. (S/840 workstation) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Product:   Unisys S/840 (Workstation) (Product introduction)Motorola 88000 (Microprocessor) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionWorkstationsReduced-Instruction-Set ComputersExport.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UNISYS PLANS TO SHIP ITS 88000-BASED UNIXandM;SYSTEMS IN US, EUROPE THIS YEARandM;Unisys Corp is discreetly shipping its new range of Motorola 88000-based RISCsystems in Japan.andP;  The new S/840 Unix machines come with a single CPU claimedto deliver 28 MIPS, Electronic News reports, although Unisys has plans toship a four-CPU version in the not-too-distant future.andP;  Shipments into Europeand the US are being postponed until the company has its hands on morecommercial applications for the systems.andP;  The Japanese shipments have so farbeen to Toyota, Nissan and Honda, for CAD/CAM applications, for which thesystems come bundled with the company's Unicad CAD/CAM software.andP;  The systemis being marketed as a &quot;technical workstation&quot; in Japan.andP;  In the US andEurope, on the other hand, the S/840 will be sold as a commercial machine -wise Unisys knows its place and has decided not to tangle with the likes ofSun Microsystems, IBM Corp, Hewlett-Packard Co and Digital Equipment Corp.andO;But, according to the 88open Consortium's Tom Mace, there are plenty ofcommercial applications already available - around 2,000 he reckons.andP;  Aconsultant with the San Jose, California newsletter RISC Management reckonsthat Unisys will have more problems with the 88000's viability as a systemsarchitecture - Andrew Allison argues that unless there is a deluge of88000-based hardware announcements over the next few months, there will neverbe widespread applications development for the chip.andP;  Until some majormanufacturers announce support for the processor, there is, in Allison'sopinion, no incentive to do software for it.andP;  According to John Chen, vicepresident of Unisys' Unix Systems Group, the base S/840 will be built on aVME bus structure, with 200Mb of storage and the Chorus Systemes SAmicrokernel operating system based on Unix System V.4, adapted formulti-processing, fault-tolerance and transaction processing.andO;</TEXT></DOC>